00:01:08.180 --> 00:01:11.030
JOHN OSBORNE: Thank you,
[? Ruchica, ?] and everyone

00:01:11.030 --> 00:01:13.210
for allowing me to be here.

00:01:13.210 --> 00:01:16.270
And I'd like to begin
today by taking you

00:01:16.270 --> 00:01:19.030
on a slightly imaginary journey.

00:01:19.030 --> 00:01:20.910
Imagine that here in
the United States,

00:01:20.910 --> 00:01:24.830
there's an outbreak
of a great pandemic.

00:01:24.830 --> 00:01:26.550
The pandemic exists
all over the world,

00:01:26.550 --> 00:01:29.650
but there are at least 300,000
or 400,000 cases of people

00:01:29.650 --> 00:01:33.200
coming down with this
disease, and 22 people

00:01:33.200 --> 00:01:37.180
are dying of it every
day in the United States.

00:01:37.180 --> 00:01:39.519
Imagine if you knew about
a pandemic like that,

00:01:39.519 --> 00:01:42.060
it would be on the front page
of the "New York Times," right?

00:01:42.060 --> 00:01:44.820
Well, actually, it does exist.

00:01:44.820 --> 00:01:47.180
Pandemic has a name.

00:01:47.180 --> 00:01:49.520
It's called Post-Traumatic
Stress Disorder.

00:01:49.520 --> 00:01:51.810
It's affected at least
300,000 or 400,000

00:01:51.810 --> 00:01:55.040
Americans coming back from
Afghanistan and Iraq, soldiers

00:01:55.040 --> 00:01:57.130
and contractors and civilians.

00:01:57.130 --> 00:02:00.430
And 22 vets a day are
committing suicide

00:02:00.430 --> 00:02:02.540
because of the effects
of this disease.

00:02:02.540 --> 00:02:03.960
So it's a big problem.

00:02:03.960 --> 00:02:05.920
And I'm part of an
organization that

00:02:05.920 --> 00:02:09.979
has one solution or one method
of dealing with this problem,

00:02:09.979 --> 00:02:12.370
and that's what I'm going
to talk to you about today.

00:02:12.370 --> 00:02:14.911
But first, I'd like to talk to
you a little bit about myself,

00:02:14.911 --> 00:02:17.270
what I'm doing here,
and why I'm here.

00:02:17.270 --> 00:02:19.780
I am a retired
venture capitalist,

00:02:19.780 --> 00:02:22.720
and so I've been spending a
lot of time in Silicon Valley.

00:02:22.720 --> 00:02:25.260
And also, I've been
meditating for about 45 years

00:02:25.260 --> 00:02:28.180
and teaching different forms of
meditation and self-development

00:02:28.180 --> 00:02:30.920
for about 40 years.

00:02:30.920 --> 00:02:32.440
Two reasons that I'm here.

00:02:32.440 --> 00:02:35.090
One has to do with a
person named Walter,

00:02:35.090 --> 00:02:36.810
whom I'm happy to
tell you about.

00:02:36.810 --> 00:02:38.890
And another has
to do with my dad.

00:02:38.890 --> 00:02:43.440
My dad was a World War II
hero in Pacific theater,

00:02:43.440 --> 00:02:46.580
was nominated for a Silver
Star for knocking down

00:02:46.580 --> 00:02:49.210
48 kamikaze planes who
were trying to shoot down

00:02:49.210 --> 00:02:55.770
his ship in 24 hours, and
always held the values

00:02:55.770 --> 00:02:58.830
of military service
as I was growing up.

00:02:58.830 --> 00:03:00.790
Now, you've probably
figured out from my age

00:03:00.790 --> 00:03:02.610
that I grew up during
the Vietnam era.

00:03:02.610 --> 00:03:05.040
And as hard as he wanted to
get me in military service,

00:03:05.040 --> 00:03:06.240
I was running the other way.

00:03:06.240 --> 00:03:07.720
I was not at all interested.

00:03:07.720 --> 00:03:10.000
And it was only because
of an experience

00:03:10.000 --> 00:03:11.605
I had with my dad late in life.

00:03:11.605 --> 00:03:13.230
Right before he died,
I took him to see

00:03:13.230 --> 00:03:14.990
the movie "Saving Private Ryan."

00:03:14.990 --> 00:03:17.610
And we had about a four-hour
conversation afterwards.

00:03:17.610 --> 00:03:19.220
And it was then
that the light went

00:03:19.220 --> 00:03:23.855
on in my mind as to why my dad
was so interested in getting

00:03:23.855 --> 00:03:25.350
me involved in the military.

00:03:25.350 --> 00:03:28.100
Because for my dad,
being in the service,

00:03:28.100 --> 00:03:30.210
as they used to
say in those days,

00:03:30.210 --> 00:03:32.836
laid the groundwork for him
for a lifetime of service.

00:03:32.836 --> 00:03:34.960
I grew up in a small
community in upstate New York,

00:03:34.960 --> 00:03:37.860
and my dad organized the
volunteer ambulance corps.

00:03:37.860 --> 00:03:41.242
And he raised money for the
Vietnam Veterans Memorial.

00:03:41.242 --> 00:03:43.450
And later on, he joined a
human development committee

00:03:43.450 --> 00:03:46.660
that took little old ladies to
the hospital when he had to.

00:03:46.660 --> 00:03:49.640
So being in the military
provided him with a basis

00:03:49.640 --> 00:03:51.117
for a lifetime of service.

00:03:51.117 --> 00:03:52.700
And it was only at
the end of his life

00:03:52.700 --> 00:03:53.860
that I understood
that when he wanted

00:03:53.860 --> 00:03:55.234
to get me in the
military, it was

00:03:55.234 --> 00:03:57.670
because he wanted me
to have those values.

00:03:57.670 --> 00:03:59.910
So when I started getting
involved with soldiers,

00:03:59.910 --> 00:04:02.650
I did it and continue to do
it in memory and in honor

00:04:02.650 --> 00:04:05.540
of my dad, who passed
away shortly thereafter.

00:04:05.540 --> 00:04:08.350
I was teaching these breathing
techniques to civilians

00:04:08.350 --> 00:04:11.982
in, it was about 1996
in Santa Barbara,

00:04:11.982 --> 00:04:13.940
when I got a call from
a psychologist who said,

00:04:13.940 --> 00:04:16.320
I think I have someone who
could use some of your breathing

00:04:16.320 --> 00:04:17.240
and meditation skills.

00:04:17.240 --> 00:04:19.323
He said, but I'm not sure
if he's suitable for you

00:04:19.323 --> 00:04:22.210
guys, for your course.

00:04:22.210 --> 00:04:23.780
And when I asked
him why, he said,

00:04:23.780 --> 00:04:27.860
because this person is
drug-addicted, he's violent,

00:04:27.860 --> 00:04:31.320
he's suicidal, he's a danger
to himself and to others.

00:04:31.320 --> 00:04:34.330
And oh, by the way,
he's a Vietnam vet.

00:04:34.330 --> 00:04:36.100
And so what I did
on that course was

00:04:36.100 --> 00:04:38.650
to give the course away so that
someone else could teach it,

00:04:38.650 --> 00:04:41.230
and I became the buddy of this
person, whose name was Walter.

00:04:41.230 --> 00:04:42.930
And he had a little
bit of a difficult time

00:04:42.930 --> 00:04:44.780
with the meditation and
the yoga and the breathing,

00:04:44.780 --> 00:04:46.290
but he got through the course.

00:04:46.290 --> 00:04:48.334
And I saw that it had
transformed him a lot.

00:04:48.334 --> 00:04:50.750
And I lost touch with Walter
until about five years later.

00:04:50.750 --> 00:04:52.596
I was doing a
meet-and-greet kind

00:04:52.596 --> 00:04:54.152
of a reception in Los Angeles.

00:04:54.152 --> 00:04:55.610
And there was a
long line of people

00:04:55.610 --> 00:04:57.050
that were coming up
to say hello to me.

00:04:57.050 --> 00:04:58.675
And all of a sudden,
I saw this person.

00:04:58.675 --> 00:04:59.970
He was about 6' 6" in a suit.

00:04:59.970 --> 00:05:01.210
And I vaguely recognized him.

00:05:01.210 --> 00:05:03.100
And he came up and
he gave me a hug

00:05:03.100 --> 00:05:04.400
and lifted me off the ground.

00:05:04.400 --> 00:05:06.140
And I'm like, who
is this person?

00:05:06.140 --> 00:05:08.680
And he said, John,
he said, I'm Walter.

00:05:08.680 --> 00:05:10.650
And Walter, by that
time, was the head

00:05:10.650 --> 00:05:13.270
of data processing services for
the county of Santa Barbara.

00:05:13.270 --> 00:05:14.330
He owned a car.

00:05:14.330 --> 00:05:15.200
He had a girlfriend.

00:05:15.200 --> 00:05:16.390
He had an apartment.

00:05:16.390 --> 00:05:19.730
He was off his drugs, and
he was leading a happy life.

00:05:19.730 --> 00:05:21.690
Now, I'm not sure what
the complete connection

00:05:21.690 --> 00:05:24.240
between the course
that I took with Walter

00:05:24.240 --> 00:05:25.674
and his present state.

00:05:25.674 --> 00:05:26.840
But it planted a seed in me.

00:05:26.840 --> 00:05:29.360
I thought, wow, for people
who are in such anguish,

00:05:29.360 --> 00:05:31.670
having such trouble being
in the present moment,

00:05:31.670 --> 00:05:33.770
this might be something
that would be useful.

00:05:33.770 --> 00:05:37.260
So about eight years
ago, I was asked again

00:05:37.260 --> 00:05:39.910
by a colleague to
join them in doing

00:05:39.910 --> 00:05:41.780
a brief introduction
at a Vet Center.

00:05:41.780 --> 00:05:43.530
For those of you who
are not very familiar

00:05:43.530 --> 00:05:45.946
with the military, since the
Vietnam War and people coming

00:05:45.946 --> 00:05:48.960
back having so much trouble
transiting to civilian life,

00:05:48.960 --> 00:05:52.070
the VA has set up these
neighborhood Vet Centers

00:05:52.070 --> 00:05:54.000
where vets can come
and talk to each other,

00:05:54.000 --> 00:05:57.620
maybe get some help with
their processing of papers,

00:05:57.620 --> 00:06:00.310
and join a group,
and meet other vets,

00:06:00.310 --> 00:06:02.340
and deal with their problems.

00:06:02.340 --> 00:06:05.280
And I taught some just
initial breathing techniques

00:06:05.280 --> 00:06:08.130
to some of these vets, and the
results were so transformative.

00:06:08.130 --> 00:06:10.132
These are people that
were running red lights

00:06:10.132 --> 00:06:12.340
in Santa Monica, California,
because they were afraid

00:06:12.340 --> 00:06:14.630
that there was an IED
at the side of the road.

00:06:14.630 --> 00:06:16.240
How many people are
familiar with PTS,

00:06:16.240 --> 00:06:18.030
some of the symptoms of PTS?

00:06:18.030 --> 00:06:21.595
Some of them are
memories which crowd out

00:06:21.595 --> 00:06:23.970
the real estate inside them
to the point where they can't

00:06:23.970 --> 00:06:26.390
be in the present moment,
emotional numbness,

00:06:26.390 --> 00:06:28.620
having trouble with extremes
in emotions, especially

00:06:28.620 --> 00:06:33.130
anger, suicidal thoughts,
depression, sleeplessness,

00:06:33.130 --> 00:06:36.895
and for a lot of them, a
tendency to self-medicate,

00:06:36.895 --> 00:06:39.360
either with drugs or alcohol.

00:06:39.360 --> 00:06:41.470
These are people
that have either

00:06:41.470 --> 00:06:46.130
seen something or lost
someone or done something

00:06:46.130 --> 00:06:49.090
that they regret
hugely, and come back.

00:06:49.090 --> 00:06:52.150
And the problem with PTS is
that it doesn't go away just

00:06:52.150 --> 00:06:53.010
by itself.

00:06:53.010 --> 00:06:55.610
I've treated a lot of vets that
were even in the Vietnam War.

00:06:55.610 --> 00:06:57.610
40 years later, they're
still having problems.

00:06:57.610 --> 00:06:59.060
I'll tell you more about
this in a little bit,

00:06:59.060 --> 00:07:01.060
but I thought you'd like to
meet some of my students.

00:07:01.060 --> 00:07:02.990
So we're going to start by
seeing a short video with some

00:07:02.990 --> 00:07:05.520
of their experiences, and then
we'll talk a little bit more

00:07:05.520 --> 00:07:06.300
about what I do.

00:07:06.300 --> 00:07:06.800
OK?

