00:19:00.139 --> 00:19:01.930
JOHN OSBORNE: So this
Power Breath workshop

00:19:01.930 --> 00:19:04.360
is a five-day workshop
that we offer for vets.

00:19:04.360 --> 00:19:06.770
It's a combination
of yoga, meditation,

00:19:06.770 --> 00:19:10.190
and a very specialized
form of rhythmic breathing

00:19:10.190 --> 00:19:12.990
called the Sudarshan
Kriya yoga technique.

00:19:12.990 --> 00:19:15.960
Most people at Google
know that breathing

00:19:15.960 --> 00:19:18.260
is one of the main
sources of energy, right?

00:19:18.260 --> 00:19:21.902
You can live for several weeks
without food, several days

00:19:21.902 --> 00:19:23.860
without water, but you
can't live for very long

00:19:23.860 --> 00:19:25.560
without breath.

00:19:25.560 --> 00:19:28.000
So breath is, we all know,
a major source of energy.

00:19:28.000 --> 00:19:29.850
It's also a major
part of our health.

00:19:29.850 --> 00:19:31.820
About 80% of the toxins
that leave the body

00:19:31.820 --> 00:19:33.236
leave the body
through the breath.

00:19:33.236 --> 00:19:35.250
But there's a third
mysterious aspect

00:19:35.250 --> 00:19:38.970
to the breath that allows this
workshop to be very powerful.

00:19:38.970 --> 00:19:42.130
And that is that the breath
is a very powerful link

00:19:42.130 --> 00:19:44.837
between the mind and the
body and the emotions.

00:19:44.837 --> 00:19:46.420
How many people have
been at a meeting

00:19:46.420 --> 00:19:48.879
at Google where you
know that somebody's not

00:19:48.879 --> 00:19:50.670
having a very good day
or not having a very

00:19:50.670 --> 00:19:52.670
good time at the meeting,
because you look over,

00:19:52.670 --> 00:19:54.936
and they're like--
[BREATHES VERY DEEPLY].

00:19:54.936 --> 00:19:56.579
And you think, in
about five seconds,

00:19:56.579 --> 00:19:58.370
I don't want to be in
this meeting anymore.

00:19:58.370 --> 00:20:00.310
How many people have had an
experience in or out of Google

00:20:00.310 --> 00:20:00.660
like that?

00:20:00.660 --> 00:20:03.076
When you see that, emotions
change and the breath changes.

00:20:03.076 --> 00:20:05.020
We see it often backwards.

00:20:05.020 --> 00:20:07.230
We see the breath
change and we think, OK,

00:20:07.230 --> 00:20:08.890
there's an emotional change.

00:20:08.890 --> 00:20:10.840
Any mothers here
with small children?

00:20:10.840 --> 00:20:11.340
Anybody?

00:20:11.340 --> 00:20:12.710
Right.

00:20:12.710 --> 00:20:14.930
And so have you ever sung
a lullaby to your child,

00:20:14.930 --> 00:20:17.780
and you see the breath getting
slower and getting longer,

00:20:17.780 --> 00:20:19.780
and you're thinking,
in 30 more seconds,

00:20:19.780 --> 00:20:22.010
my child is finally
going to sleep?

00:20:22.010 --> 00:20:23.490
So there's this important link.

00:20:23.490 --> 00:20:26.290
And it's that link that we use
in the Power Breath workshop.

00:20:26.290 --> 00:20:29.930
Because most of the time, we
notice the emotional change,

00:20:29.930 --> 00:20:34.050
and then we notice the change
in the rhythm of the breath.

00:20:34.050 --> 00:20:36.080
But we teach specific
rhythms of the breath

00:20:36.080 --> 00:20:39.190
to the vets, which allow them
to come to a center place

00:20:39.190 --> 00:20:41.200
no matter what else is
going on in their life,

00:20:41.200 --> 00:20:43.020
and to come back in
the present moment.

00:20:43.020 --> 00:20:44.170
These are people
that are trapped

00:20:44.170 --> 00:20:46.295
in their memories and their
physiological reactions

00:20:46.295 --> 00:20:46.874
to the past.

00:20:46.874 --> 00:20:48.290
I said at the
beginning, these are

00:20:48.290 --> 00:20:51.807
people that run red
lights in Los Angeles,

00:20:51.807 --> 00:20:54.390
because they're afraid there's
a bomb at the side of the road.

00:20:54.390 --> 00:20:58.330
They're not able to live
in the present at all.

00:20:58.330 --> 00:21:01.300
Most of us, our mind swings
from the past to the future,

00:21:01.300 --> 00:21:03.480
and sometimes lives in
the present, hopefully.

00:21:03.480 --> 00:21:05.770
But for them, their mind
is trapped in the past.

00:21:05.770 --> 00:21:09.130
And these rhythmic breaths, the
[? Sky ?] Sudarshan Kriya yoga

00:21:09.130 --> 00:21:12.180
breath work not only
brings them to the present

00:21:12.180 --> 00:21:14.340
but allows the body
naturally to begin

00:21:14.340 --> 00:21:17.980
to let go of trauma and
stress-- not just in that day,

00:21:17.980 --> 00:21:19.460
but on a permanent basis.

00:21:19.460 --> 00:21:21.330
And they refer to some research.

00:21:21.330 --> 00:21:23.900
There's just been one pilot
study done on this program.

00:21:23.900 --> 00:21:26.731
It was done at the Center for
the Study of the Healthy Mind,

00:21:26.731 --> 00:21:28.730
Dr. Richard Davidson--
some of you may know him.

00:21:28.730 --> 00:21:30.271
I think he's actually
come and spoken

00:21:30.271 --> 00:21:32.480
at Google-- at the
University of Wisconsin.

00:21:32.480 --> 00:21:35.350
And that research showed,
with a control group

00:21:35.350 --> 00:21:38.500
of 10 vets taking the course and
10 vets doing something else,

00:21:38.500 --> 00:21:41.320
over a period of seven
days, that their symptoms

00:21:41.320 --> 00:21:45.420
of Post-Traumatic Stress lowered
on an average of 40% to 50%.

00:21:45.420 --> 00:21:46.480
That's interesting.

00:21:46.480 --> 00:21:48.979
But what is also interesting
is that when they measured them

00:21:48.979 --> 00:21:51.380
six months later, the
symptoms were still lower.

00:21:51.380 --> 00:21:53.210
And when they measured
them a year later,

00:21:53.210 --> 00:21:54.710
the symptoms were still lower.

00:21:54.710 --> 00:21:57.190
Now, it's still too early to
know what that pilot means.

00:21:57.190 --> 00:22:00.020
But it means generally
that their experience

00:22:00.020 --> 00:22:01.990
of their own trauma,
the sleeplessness,

00:22:01.990 --> 00:22:04.910
the hyper-arousal,
the flash to anger

00:22:04.910 --> 00:22:06.237
was lessened during the course.

00:22:06.237 --> 00:22:08.320
And whether or not they
practiced these techniques

00:22:08.320 --> 00:22:11.940
afterwards, that
level of symptom

00:22:11.940 --> 00:22:15.350
was still lower after six
months and after a year.

00:22:15.350 --> 00:22:18.360
So now, eight years later,
we've taught about 1,000 vets.

00:22:18.360 --> 00:22:24.000
And we are training teachers
as fast as we can, because,

00:22:24.000 --> 00:22:26.322
as I said earlier, there's
300,000 to 400,000 people

00:22:26.322 --> 00:22:28.030
walking around with
Post-Traumatic Stress

00:22:28.030 --> 00:22:29.440
from these wars.

00:22:29.440 --> 00:22:32.940
And a lot of them don't want to
be on drugs, because the drugs

00:22:32.940 --> 00:22:35.870
have a lot of side effects,
and they mask the symptoms,

00:22:35.870 --> 00:22:38.370
but they don't really
cure the cause.

00:22:38.370 --> 00:22:40.175
And they don't want
to go-- especially

00:22:40.175 --> 00:22:42.050
if they're still in the
service for-- there's

00:22:42.050 --> 00:22:44.690
a great stigma for going
for psychiatric care.

00:22:44.690 --> 00:22:47.720
So programs like these
provide an alternate way

00:22:47.720 --> 00:22:49.480
of dealing with the
Post-Traumatic Stress.

00:22:49.480 --> 00:22:51.021
And as I said earlier,
it's something

00:22:51.021 --> 00:22:53.250
that they can do by
themselves for themselves.

00:22:53.250 --> 00:22:56.060
So it's a program that
the soldiers like a lot.

00:22:56.060 --> 00:22:58.470
I thought I'd teach you
maybe one of the very

00:22:58.470 --> 00:23:01.089
preliminary forms of
breathing, if you'd

00:23:01.089 --> 00:23:02.380
like to have that demonstrated.

00:23:02.380 --> 00:23:04.330
I was just at the
Aspen Brain Forum,

00:23:04.330 --> 00:23:06.417
and I thought I had made
it safely off the stage,

00:23:06.417 --> 00:23:09.000
and I was just ready to step off
the stage, and somebody said,

00:23:09.000 --> 00:23:11.090
can you show us one of
the forms of breathing

00:23:11.090 --> 00:23:12.930
that the soldiers do?

00:23:12.930 --> 00:23:15.402
So this is a form of yogic
breathing called Bhastrika.

00:23:15.402 --> 00:23:17.610
How many people would like
to learn just a little bit

00:23:17.610 --> 00:23:18.380
about it?

00:23:18.380 --> 00:23:18.470
OK.

00:23:18.470 --> 00:23:20.136
So sit back in your
chairs a little bit.

00:23:20.136 --> 00:23:21.650
Sit up.

00:23:21.650 --> 00:23:24.240
And we're going to breathe
in and out through the nose.

00:23:24.240 --> 00:23:25.620
This is a form of breathing
that will give you

00:23:25.620 --> 00:23:26.578
a little bit of energy.

00:23:26.578 --> 00:23:29.497
In Southern California, it's
nicknamed the Starbucks breath.

00:23:29.497 --> 00:23:31.830
So we're going to put our
hands in baby fists like this.

00:23:31.830 --> 00:23:32.190
Yeah?

00:23:32.190 --> 00:23:33.856
And we're going to
breathe in, and we're

00:23:33.856 --> 00:23:35.730
going to allow
our hands to go up

00:23:35.730 --> 00:23:38.040
into what I call the
Glory Hallelujah pose.

00:23:38.040 --> 00:23:41.170
And then we're going to
grasp an imaginary bar

00:23:41.170 --> 00:23:43.010
and breathe out through
the nose sharply.

00:23:43.010 --> 00:23:44.180
Come down.

00:23:44.180 --> 00:23:46.500
Breathe in and go up.

00:23:46.500 --> 00:23:48.290
Exhale, come down.

00:23:48.290 --> 00:23:51.780
And we'll do it in rhythm, and
we'll do maybe 10 repetitions.

00:23:51.780 --> 00:23:52.630
Should we do that?

00:23:52.630 --> 00:23:53.130
OK.

00:23:53.130 --> 00:23:58.019
Take a normal breath in and out.

00:23:58.019 --> 00:23:59.560
Let's see if we can
do this together.

00:23:59.560 --> 00:24:00.860
Ready, begin.

00:24:00.860 --> 00:24:05.240
In, out, in, out, in, out.

00:24:05.240 --> 00:24:06.875
And put a little energy into it.

00:24:20.440 --> 00:24:21.530
And relax.

00:24:21.530 --> 00:24:22.910
Close your eyes.

00:24:22.910 --> 00:24:24.785
Take a transition breath
in through the nose.

00:24:27.740 --> 00:24:30.140
And out.

00:24:30.140 --> 00:24:32.390
And just close your eyes and
see if you feel somewhere

00:24:32.390 --> 00:24:35.730
inside a little bit more energy
than you had 10 minutes ago.

00:24:44.130 --> 00:24:46.628
Open the eyes.

00:24:46.628 --> 00:24:48.235
You can even do
this at your cubicle

00:24:48.235 --> 00:24:50.120
if nobody thinks
you're looking too

00:24:50.120 --> 00:24:51.760
strange in the middle
of the afternoon.

00:24:51.760 --> 00:24:53.426
Instead of going to
get a cup of coffee,

00:24:53.426 --> 00:24:55.334
you can do maybe
three sets of 15 to 20

00:24:55.334 --> 00:24:57.250
of these with a little
bit of rest in between.

00:24:57.250 --> 00:24:59.890
Not something you'd like to
go home and do for 45 minutes

00:24:59.890 --> 00:25:01.460
while you're watching
TV, you know.

00:25:01.460 --> 00:25:03.620
Three sets of maybe 10 to 15.

00:25:03.620 --> 00:25:06.852
I thought maybe, too,
you'd like to experience

00:25:06.852 --> 00:25:09.060
a kind of guided meditation
that we do with the vets.

00:25:09.060 --> 00:25:10.143
Would you like to do that?

00:25:10.143 --> 00:25:11.190
OK.

00:25:11.190 --> 00:25:12.917
We'll do this for
maybe 10 to 15 minutes,

00:25:12.917 --> 00:25:15.250
and then I'll be around to
answer any questions that you

00:25:15.250 --> 00:25:16.208
have about the program.

00:25:18.564 --> 00:25:20.980
So anyone who came in late,
if you'd have your cell phones

00:25:20.980 --> 00:25:22.710
turned to vibrate,
that would be great.

00:25:22.710 --> 00:25:25.704
Can everybody see me OK?

00:25:25.704 --> 00:25:28.120
So all you have to do with
this guided meditation is close

00:25:28.120 --> 00:25:31.900
your eyes and
follow instructions.

00:25:31.900 --> 00:25:35.520
Let's sit comfortably with
both our feet on the floor,

00:25:35.520 --> 00:25:41.830
spine straight, palms up
on the lap, eyes closed.

00:25:41.830 --> 00:25:44.700
Let's begin by taking a normal
breath in through the nose.

00:25:47.460 --> 00:25:48.460
And out.

00:25:53.440 --> 00:26:02.180
Begin by finding ourselves
in this environment,

00:26:02.180 --> 00:26:10.840
listening to all the noises
around us-- conversations

00:26:10.840 --> 00:26:21.195
from the other room, the hum
of the electrical system.

00:26:28.250 --> 00:26:30.600
And feel that connection
between our body and the chair

00:26:30.600 --> 00:26:31.308
we're sitting on.

00:27:07.439 --> 00:27:09.730
Now perhaps you're feeling
a little bit more in harmony

00:27:09.730 --> 00:27:10.646
with your environment.

00:27:35.520 --> 00:27:37.170
Become aware of
your physical body.

00:27:52.110 --> 00:27:53.910
It may be feeling tired.

00:27:53.910 --> 00:27:55.710
It may be feeling rested.

00:27:55.710 --> 00:27:58.780
It may be feeling
a little agitated.

00:27:58.780 --> 00:28:01.445
There could be some
aches or pains or twinges

00:28:01.445 --> 00:28:05.190
in certain parts of the body.

00:28:05.190 --> 00:28:07.320
Just be with your body
just as it is right now.

00:28:38.560 --> 00:28:40.720
Innocently, put your
awareness on your right foot.

00:28:47.906 --> 00:28:48.894
Right knee.

00:28:54.830 --> 00:28:56.402
Right thigh and hip.

00:29:07.240 --> 00:29:07.780
Left foot.

00:29:15.560 --> 00:29:16.540
Left knee.

00:29:23.240 --> 00:29:24.819
Left thigh and hip.

00:29:35.090 --> 00:29:35.590
Stomach.

00:29:42.390 --> 00:29:42.890
Abdomen.

00:29:49.231 --> 00:29:49.730
Chest.

00:29:57.770 --> 00:29:58.550
Right arm.

00:30:05.280 --> 00:30:05.880
And shoulder.

00:30:12.440 --> 00:30:13.075
Left arm.

00:30:18.520 --> 00:30:19.440
And shoulder.

00:30:35.083 --> 00:30:35.583
Face.

00:30:41.106 --> 00:30:41.980
Between the eyebrows.

00:30:50.160 --> 00:30:51.650
Top of the head.

00:30:58.745 --> 00:30:59.245
Whole body.

00:31:05.680 --> 00:31:08.620
Allow your awareness
to flow like a river

00:31:08.620 --> 00:31:10.120
through your whole body.

00:31:21.054 --> 00:31:26.360
The top of your head to
the soles of your feet.

00:31:26.360 --> 00:31:27.775
Through your whole body.

00:32:12.141 --> 00:32:13.390
Become aware of your thoughts.

00:32:35.050 --> 00:32:40.028
Positive thoughts,
negative thoughts,

00:32:40.028 --> 00:32:43.350
it doesn't much matter.

00:32:43.350 --> 00:32:46.150
Just watch them flow by
like they're in a river,

00:32:46.150 --> 00:32:49.850
and don't try to control them
or judge them in any way.

00:33:30.330 --> 00:33:34.060
Underneath our thoughts,
we all have feelings.

00:33:34.060 --> 00:33:38.300
Allow yourself to become
aware of your feelings.

00:34:03.190 --> 00:34:08.350
Happy feelings, sad
feelings, anxious feelings,

00:34:08.350 --> 00:34:12.323
angry feelings,
peaceful feelings.

00:34:12.323 --> 00:34:14.614
Whatever kind of feelings
are there, just observe them.

00:35:04.350 --> 00:35:07.260
Underneath the bodily
sensations and the thoughts

00:35:07.260 --> 00:35:11.650
and the feelings, there's a
deeper place within each of us.

00:35:14.870 --> 00:35:18.404
Deep and silent like an ocean.

00:35:18.404 --> 00:35:21.710
Allow yourself to drop into
that deeper, silent place.

00:35:47.720 --> 00:35:50.930
In that deep, silent
place, there's

00:35:50.930 --> 00:35:53.490
a well of peace and joy.

00:37:35.190 --> 00:37:37.575
Once again, put your
awareness on your feelings.

00:38:00.800 --> 00:38:02.070
Become aware of your thoughts.

00:38:21.810 --> 00:38:23.365
Become aware of
your physical body.

00:38:45.760 --> 00:38:47.070
Take a breath in.

00:38:49.670 --> 00:38:50.525
And let go.

00:38:54.990 --> 00:38:57.791
Begin to become aware of the
environment in which you find

00:38:57.791 --> 00:38:58.290
yourselves.

00:39:19.620 --> 00:39:22.532
Feel once again the contact
of your body with the seat

00:39:22.532 --> 00:39:23.490
that you're sitting on.

00:39:43.703 --> 00:39:47.715
Take another deep breath in.

00:39:47.715 --> 00:39:51.290
And let go.

00:39:51.290 --> 00:39:52.550
Begin to stretch a little.

00:39:52.550 --> 00:39:56.040
You can wiggle your
fingers and your toes.

00:39:56.040 --> 00:39:58.360
Move in your chair a little bit.

00:39:58.360 --> 00:40:02.160
And taking your own time,
as much time as you need,

00:40:02.160 --> 00:40:05.812
you can slowly and
gradually open your eyes.

00:40:33.380 --> 00:40:35.892
It was good?

00:40:35.892 --> 00:40:37.890
Great.

00:40:37.890 --> 00:40:39.950
I forgot to ask if there
are any vets present.

00:40:39.950 --> 00:40:42.270
Anyone here?

00:40:42.270 --> 00:40:43.766
So whenever I see
a vet in uniform

00:40:43.766 --> 00:40:46.390
at an airport or anywhere else,
I always take the opportunity--

00:40:46.390 --> 00:40:48.681
although, it always embarrasses
them-- to say thank you

00:40:48.681 --> 00:40:50.890
for your service to our country.

00:40:50.890 --> 00:40:53.380
I was talking to someone who
was born in a foreign country,

00:40:53.380 --> 00:40:57.670
and they were trying to
decide whether they wanted

00:40:57.670 --> 00:41:02.250
to contribute and
support our organization.

00:41:02.250 --> 00:41:04.912
And they said, well, you know,
I give to my home country.

00:41:04.912 --> 00:41:06.620
I give lots of things
to my home country.

00:41:06.620 --> 00:41:09.899
And I said, well, while
you're here in Silicon Valley,

00:41:09.899 --> 00:41:11.940
it's not your home country
that's protecting you,

00:41:11.940 --> 00:41:14.060
it's the American
servicemen and women

00:41:14.060 --> 00:41:15.320
who have risked their lives.

00:41:15.320 --> 00:41:17.270
And coming back,
they're the people

00:41:17.270 --> 00:41:19.360
that can really use our help.

00:41:19.360 --> 00:41:21.010
They've stuck their
necks out for us,

00:41:21.010 --> 00:41:22.630
risked their lives for us.

00:41:22.630 --> 00:41:26.140
And it's now time for us
to be able to help them

00:41:26.140 --> 00:41:28.670
in whatever way we can.

00:41:28.670 --> 00:41:32.422
I want to tell you just one
or two more stories from-- one

00:41:32.422 --> 00:41:34.380
came up for me during
meditation about the vets

00:41:34.380 --> 00:41:36.970
that I've been lucky enough to
work with, and then to tell you

00:41:36.970 --> 00:41:40.600
why I'm here at Google today.

00:41:40.600 --> 00:41:41.810
I had a Vietnam vet.

00:41:41.810 --> 00:41:45.090
He wasn't in this film,
but he was a dog handler

00:41:45.090 --> 00:41:47.680
in Vietnam, which meant that he
had a dog that he worked with.

00:41:47.680 --> 00:41:50.090
And they'd send the dogs
into the Viet Cong tunnels,

00:41:50.090 --> 00:41:52.810
and they'd come
out the other end.

00:41:52.810 --> 00:41:54.626
And one day, he sent
his dog into a tunnel,

00:41:54.626 --> 00:41:56.250
and a whole bunch of
Viet Cong came out

00:41:56.250 --> 00:41:58.560
the other end of the tunnel, and
they started shooting at him.

00:41:58.560 --> 00:42:00.210
He wasn't really a combatant,
but he had a weapon,

00:42:00.210 --> 00:42:01.020
and he shot back.

00:42:01.020 --> 00:42:02.540
And when they did
the body count,

00:42:02.540 --> 00:42:04.684
he had a special
weapon, so he knew

00:42:04.684 --> 00:42:07.100
who had been killed by other
people and who he had killed.

00:42:07.100 --> 00:42:08.600
And one of the
people he had killed,

00:42:08.600 --> 00:42:12.167
unfortunately, was a
13-year-old Vietnamese girl.

00:42:12.167 --> 00:42:14.000
And on the last day of
this five-day course,

00:42:14.000 --> 00:42:16.440
he came up to me and he
grabbed me and he shook me,

00:42:16.440 --> 00:42:17.090
this guy did.

00:42:17.090 --> 00:42:18.520
He was about 70 years old.

00:42:18.520 --> 00:42:21.335
And he said, she's
gone, she's gone.

00:42:21.335 --> 00:42:23.322
And I'm like, who's gone?

00:42:23.322 --> 00:42:25.280
And he said, that girl
I killed, he said, she's

00:42:25.280 --> 00:42:28.520
been in my dreams every
night for the last 40 years.

00:42:28.520 --> 00:42:31.020
And last night was the first
night I slept through the night

00:42:31.020 --> 00:42:32.440
and she didn't come
back in my dreams.

00:42:32.440 --> 00:42:34.980
So imagine what it would be
like to live a life like that,

00:42:34.980 --> 00:42:37.640
and then to live a life
free of that kind of thing.

00:42:37.640 --> 00:42:41.000
Another Vietnam vet I taught,
when he did this breathing

00:42:41.000 --> 00:42:44.060
for the first time, he
experienced a memory

00:42:44.060 --> 00:42:46.591
that he had repressed
ever since Vietnam.

00:42:46.591 --> 00:42:48.090
He had forgotten
completely about it

00:42:48.090 --> 00:42:51.292
where a hand grenade had
come down in a foxhole

00:42:51.292 --> 00:42:53.500
that he was in, and he had
thrown the hand grenade up

00:42:53.500 --> 00:42:56.495
in the air, and saved
himself and his comrades

00:42:56.495 --> 00:42:57.120
in the process.

00:42:57.120 --> 00:42:59.794
And it exploded about
30 feet above his head.

00:42:59.794 --> 00:43:01.210
And he said, during
the breathing,

00:43:01.210 --> 00:43:03.770
not only did he smell the
sulfur of the grenade--

00:43:03.770 --> 00:43:05.800
I think that's sort of
an interesting fact.

00:43:05.800 --> 00:43:08.200
He said, but there was
a whole part of his mind

00:43:08.200 --> 00:43:10.860
that had been trapped behind
this repressed memory, he said,

00:43:10.860 --> 00:43:12.240
that started to come
out during the course.

00:43:12.240 --> 00:43:14.580
He had access to it for
the first time in 40 years.

00:43:14.580 --> 00:43:16.829
And he got actually a little
angry at the instructors.

00:43:16.829 --> 00:43:18.371
He said, where were
you 40 years ago?

00:43:18.371 --> 00:43:19.745
He said, my whole
life would have

00:43:19.745 --> 00:43:22.130
been different had I had
access to this particular part

00:43:22.130 --> 00:43:23.614
of my mind.

00:43:23.614 --> 00:43:25.780
So there's a lot of people
out there waiting for us.

00:43:25.780 --> 00:43:28.970
And a lot of people in
American corporations,

00:43:28.970 --> 00:43:32.880
especially in Silicon Valley,
are taking an interest in vets.

00:43:32.880 --> 00:43:35.621
I spoke to Vets
Network at Cisco.

00:43:35.621 --> 00:43:37.870
I don't know if there's a
Vets Network here at Google.

00:43:37.870 --> 00:43:40.820
But I spoke to one, and they're
reaching out to other vets

00:43:40.820 --> 00:43:41.720
to help other vets.

00:43:41.720 --> 00:43:43.220
And when I was at
Microsoft, they

00:43:43.220 --> 00:43:44.565
sponsored a course in Seattle.

00:43:44.565 --> 00:43:46.440
So maybe there's some
people in this audience

00:43:46.440 --> 00:43:47.559
that would like to help.

00:43:47.559 --> 00:43:49.100
We're a volunteer-based
organization.

00:43:49.100 --> 00:43:50.766
We don't charge the
vets for what we do,

00:43:50.766 --> 00:43:53.212
but that means we rely on
lots of different volunteers

00:43:53.212 --> 00:43:54.420
for lots of different things.

00:43:54.420 --> 00:43:55.961
So if anybody here
thinks that they'd

00:43:55.961 --> 00:43:58.100
like to get involved and
help vets, as I said,

00:43:58.100 --> 00:44:00.060
there are 300,000
or 400,000 vets out

00:44:00.060 --> 00:44:01.380
there who need our help.

00:44:01.380 --> 00:44:04.670
And I can use the
brain power at Google,

00:44:04.670 --> 00:44:08.050
I'm sure, to figure out new
ways to help reach out to them.

00:44:08.050 --> 00:44:11.600
I thought I'd just
save 5 or 10 minutes

00:44:11.600 --> 00:44:13.100
to see if anybody
has any questions.

00:44:13.100 --> 00:44:15.994
And there's no question that's
impolite or too direct to ask.

00:44:15.994 --> 00:44:17.410
I'd be really
grateful if somebody

00:44:17.410 --> 00:44:18.400
had a couple of
questions that they

00:44:18.400 --> 00:44:19.840
want to ask me
about the program.

00:44:19.840 --> 00:44:20.339
Yeah?

00:44:20.339 --> 00:44:21.786
MALE SPEAKER: Mic please.

00:44:21.786 --> 00:44:23.160
AUDIENCE: So at
Google, we always

00:44:23.160 --> 00:44:25.710
think about scaling things.

00:44:25.710 --> 00:44:29.150
And I'm just wondering,
have you tried

00:44:29.150 --> 00:44:32.520
to get this into the
out-processing process

00:44:32.520 --> 00:44:34.994
within the military
organizations themselves?

00:44:34.994 --> 00:44:35.910
JOHN OSBORNE: We have.

00:44:35.910 --> 00:44:37.780
And there's some people
at very high levels.

00:44:37.780 --> 00:44:39.240
I mean, the head of the
Joint Chiefs of Staff

00:44:39.240 --> 00:44:40.960
has seen our program
and is acting about it.

00:44:40.960 --> 00:44:42.418
But if you've been
in the military,

00:44:42.418 --> 00:44:45.700
you know things don't happen
necessarily at breakneck speed.

00:44:45.700 --> 00:44:47.482
So yeah.

00:44:47.482 --> 00:44:49.440
Some people at very high
levels are aware of us

00:44:49.440 --> 00:44:50.350
and are watching us.

00:44:50.350 --> 00:44:52.840
It could be a little
while before they--

00:44:52.840 --> 00:44:55.310
but in the VA, the Veterans
Administration for people

00:44:55.310 --> 00:44:57.020
who have been released
from the military,

00:44:57.020 --> 00:44:58.645
there are different
layers of treatment

00:44:58.645 --> 00:45:01.206
that are like the
layers of an onion.

00:45:01.206 --> 00:45:02.580
And the outermost
one of these is

00:45:02.580 --> 00:45:05.121
the neighborhood Vet Centers,
which you may be familiar with.

00:45:05.121 --> 00:45:07.540
And slowly but surely,
people at these Vet Centers

00:45:07.540 --> 00:45:09.750
are sponsoring courses
and sending their people

00:45:09.750 --> 00:45:10.740
to our courses.

00:45:10.740 --> 00:45:14.040
And that's our way into the VA,
because then the VA hospitals

00:45:14.040 --> 00:45:16.870
want to do research on us,
and then it goes straight up.

00:45:16.870 --> 00:45:19.120
But it could take
a little while.

00:45:19.120 --> 00:45:20.100
That's all right.

00:45:20.100 --> 00:45:21.350
I have a little time.

00:45:21.350 --> 00:45:25.110
And I never thought when
we taught our first course

00:45:25.110 --> 00:45:28.570
that we would have
taught 1,000 vets by now.

00:45:28.570 --> 00:45:31.230
But there's 1,000 down
and 300,000 to go,

00:45:31.230 --> 00:45:33.230
so we have a ways to go.

00:45:33.230 --> 00:45:35.640
Scalability, there's
several factors.

00:45:35.640 --> 00:45:37.690
I know you're great at
analysis here in Google.

00:45:37.690 --> 00:45:40.030
One is training teachers
who are good at working

00:45:40.030 --> 00:45:42.270
with this population.

00:45:42.270 --> 00:45:44.207
Vets come in not trusting
very many people.

00:45:44.207 --> 00:45:45.540
They don't trust the government.

00:45:45.540 --> 00:45:46.819
They don't trust the military.

00:45:46.819 --> 00:45:49.110
They have a really hard time
relating to civilian life,

00:45:49.110 --> 00:45:51.570
because their values and
experiences are so different.

00:45:51.570 --> 00:45:54.410
So you need to find teachers
that can-- especially vets.

00:45:54.410 --> 00:45:56.310
And we're training
vets to be teachers now

00:45:56.310 --> 00:45:58.420
who can reach out
and relate to vets.

00:45:58.420 --> 00:46:01.340
So it takes a certain amount
of skill to teach teachers.

00:46:01.340 --> 00:46:04.090
And also, obviously,
finances are a factor,

00:46:04.090 --> 00:46:06.660
because we have to not
only train teachers

00:46:06.660 --> 00:46:09.130
but have them travel
around to where vets are.

00:46:09.130 --> 00:46:11.920
And access to government
resources and government

00:46:11.920 --> 00:46:12.840
places.

00:46:12.840 --> 00:46:14.880
I had somebody call me--
it broke my heart-- who

00:46:14.880 --> 00:46:18.870
was in the middle of a PTSD
residency program in a VA

00:46:18.870 --> 00:46:21.090
hospital, and we couldn't
get in to teach him.

00:46:21.090 --> 00:46:22.750
He was like, I need your help.

00:46:22.750 --> 00:46:23.750
Please come and help me.

00:46:23.750 --> 00:46:26.230
But we couldn't get access
to that particular part

00:46:26.230 --> 00:46:27.320
of the program.

00:46:27.320 --> 00:46:29.900
So government access,
funds, and the ability

00:46:29.900 --> 00:46:31.550
to train many more teachers.

00:46:31.550 --> 00:46:33.579
I think that the
vets that we teach

00:46:33.579 --> 00:46:35.370
will become the inheritors
of this program.

00:46:35.370 --> 00:46:37.599
I think it will eventually
be vet-run by people

00:46:37.599 --> 00:46:38.890
who graduated from the program.

00:46:38.890 --> 00:46:41.157
And I'm really
working as hard as I

00:46:41.157 --> 00:46:43.240
can to make sure that
happens as soon as possible.

00:46:43.240 --> 00:46:45.830
AUDIENCE: The thousand you've
been able to touch and teach,

00:46:45.830 --> 00:46:47.417
is it regional or global?

00:46:47.417 --> 00:46:49.250
JOHN OSBORNE: It's
interesting you say that,

00:46:49.250 --> 00:46:52.380
because it started out
just in the United States.

00:46:52.380 --> 00:46:56.570
But someone made a documentary
film of us in Europe.

00:46:56.570 --> 00:46:59.080
It was actually about the
work of Richard Davidson, who

00:46:59.080 --> 00:47:01.590
did our research, but it
included one of our workshops.

00:47:01.590 --> 00:47:05.100
And so now we're teaching all
over Europe, and especially

00:47:05.100 --> 00:47:08.030
in Eastern Europe and
Sarajevo and places like that

00:47:08.030 --> 00:47:09.330
where there's a lot of PTS.

00:47:09.330 --> 00:47:12.630
And we just trained our first
two teachers in Australia.

00:47:12.630 --> 00:47:14.070
It's also been taught in Russia.

00:47:14.070 --> 00:47:17.680
It's also been taught
in-- it's beginning

00:47:17.680 --> 00:47:19.570
to be taught in South
America as well.

00:47:19.570 --> 00:47:21.020
So it's beginning to be global.

00:47:21.020 --> 00:47:23.670
But right now, it's strongest
in the United States.

00:47:23.670 --> 00:47:26.310
We're the ones who have the
most veterans coming back

00:47:26.310 --> 00:47:28.730
from the latest wars.

00:47:28.730 --> 00:47:31.850
AUDIENCE: So yes, also, thank
you very much for what you do.

00:47:31.850 --> 00:47:34.360
So my stepbrother was in Iraq.

00:47:34.360 --> 00:47:38.760
And I know for a fact
that he suffers from it.

00:47:38.760 --> 00:47:43.150
He hasn't been diagnosed with
PTSD, but he was a medic.

00:47:43.150 --> 00:47:51.310
And I don't know how to--
I believe in my heart

00:47:51.310 --> 00:47:54.930
this would help him, but I
don't know how to approach it.

00:47:54.930 --> 00:47:58.484
And I was wondering if you
could speak of-- because there

00:47:58.484 --> 00:47:59.900
was themes in the
