00:47:59.900 --> 00:48:03.230
who had taken the
program of seeing it

00:48:03.230 --> 00:48:08.040
as hokey and kind of-- it's
a lot of times associated

00:48:08.040 --> 00:48:10.110
with pseudoscience, in a way.

00:48:10.110 --> 00:48:16.725
And how do you introduce
it to vets that are--

00:48:16.725 --> 00:48:18.475
where this is a
completely new thing and--

00:48:18.475 --> 00:48:19.345
JOHN OSBORNE: And
they're skeptical.

00:48:19.345 --> 00:48:19.690
Right.

00:48:19.690 --> 00:48:20.190
Yeah.

00:48:20.190 --> 00:48:21.655
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:48:21.655 --> 00:48:23.950
JOHN OSBORNE: First is that
they can go to the website.

00:48:23.950 --> 00:48:26.220
They can see this
film for themselves.

00:48:26.220 --> 00:48:29.190
And secondly, we can put them,
if they write into the website,

00:48:29.190 --> 00:48:31.334
in touch with a vet
who's taken the course.

00:48:31.334 --> 00:48:33.000
And there's something
about vets talking

00:48:33.000 --> 00:48:35.220
to vets which has
instant credibility.

00:48:35.220 --> 00:48:36.830
This fellow Roger,
the one who said,

00:48:36.830 --> 00:48:39.100
I don't know how it works,
I don't know why it works,

00:48:39.100 --> 00:48:40.230
we sent him around.

00:48:40.230 --> 00:48:42.630
And he just went to a
Vets Center in Texas

00:48:42.630 --> 00:48:45.310
and sat in to a vets
support group, and said,

00:48:45.310 --> 00:48:46.940
my name's Roger,
I'm a Vietnam vet,

00:48:46.940 --> 00:48:48.830
I used to be on 20
different medications,

00:48:48.830 --> 00:48:50.420
I'm not on any
medications anymore.

00:48:50.420 --> 00:48:52.490
And they're like,
where do I sign up?

00:48:52.490 --> 00:48:54.040
So vets have a lot
of credibility.

00:48:54.040 --> 00:48:56.200
And if we can put him
in touch with one who's

00:48:56.200 --> 00:48:58.234
taken the course,
they trust each other.

00:48:58.234 --> 00:48:59.900
They don't trust very
much else in life,

00:48:59.900 --> 00:49:01.140
but they trust each other.

00:49:01.140 --> 00:49:02.530
So either the website.

00:49:02.530 --> 00:49:06.684
Or I have business cards if you
want to get in touch with me,

00:49:06.684 --> 00:49:08.350
I'll put him in direct
touch with a vet.

00:49:08.350 --> 00:49:11.197
But there has to be at least
a little interest on his part.

00:49:11.197 --> 00:49:13.780
Just if you tell them they can
get off their drugs-- what they

00:49:13.780 --> 00:49:15.238
don't tell you
about these drugs is

00:49:15.238 --> 00:49:16.820
that they have
many side effects.

00:49:16.820 --> 00:49:18.980
Some people have been on
them for 30 or 40 years.

00:49:18.980 --> 00:49:20.740
And one of them is
sexual dysfunction.

00:49:20.740 --> 00:49:22.640
They don't talk about it much,
but if you can get them off--

00:49:22.640 --> 00:49:24.806
you know, if they think
they can get off those drugs

00:49:24.806 --> 00:49:27.816
and have a life again,
it's pretty motivating.

00:49:27.816 --> 00:49:29.550
AUDIENCE: You
thought that it was

00:49:29.550 --> 00:49:31.912
a wonderful way of
servicing people who

00:49:31.912 --> 00:49:32.990
were returning from war.

00:49:32.990 --> 00:49:34.504
How did you get into meditation?

00:49:34.504 --> 00:49:35.670
JOHN OSBORNE: Way back when?

00:49:35.670 --> 00:49:36.602
AUDIENCE: Yeah.

00:49:36.602 --> 00:49:39.102
JOHN OSBORNE: I was teaching a
program called Outward Bound.

00:49:39.102 --> 00:49:40.810
Some of you may know
about Outward Bound.

00:49:40.810 --> 00:49:43.140
But it's a program of take
people out in the wilderness

00:49:43.140 --> 00:49:45.817
and develop skills, you know,
self-confidence, and things.

00:49:45.817 --> 00:49:47.650
And I was teaching kids
from the inner city,

00:49:47.650 --> 00:49:50.090
and it was a really
high-stress situation.

00:49:50.090 --> 00:49:53.490
And we didn't have any time off,
and the kids were demanding,

00:49:53.490 --> 00:49:56.700
and you're pretty exhausted
all the time in a wilderness

00:49:56.700 --> 00:49:58.310
environment keeping them safe.

00:49:58.310 --> 00:50:01.100
And I noticed that
one of my colleagues

00:50:01.100 --> 00:50:02.320
had more energy than I did.

00:50:02.320 --> 00:50:04.799
His sense of humor
was indestructible.

00:50:04.799 --> 00:50:05.840
He gave more to the kids.

00:50:05.840 --> 00:50:06.680
He got more back.

00:50:06.680 --> 00:50:09.120
And so it being the '60s, I
took him aside and asked him

00:50:09.120 --> 00:50:12.020
what drug he was on, you
know, what he was doing.

00:50:12.020 --> 00:50:14.180
And he said, it's this
thing that I do twice a day

00:50:14.180 --> 00:50:15.640
for 20 minutes, this meditation.

00:50:15.640 --> 00:50:17.460
And I said, that
sounds really weird.

00:50:17.460 --> 00:50:21.100
And if it sounds weird in 2010,
it sounded much stranger back

00:50:21.100 --> 00:50:22.482
in the late-60s.

00:50:22.482 --> 00:50:23.940
And then he did
something for which

00:50:23.940 --> 00:50:25.120
I'll be forever
grateful, because he

00:50:25.120 --> 00:50:25.700
was a really good friend.

00:50:25.700 --> 00:50:27.057
He put his arm on my shoulder.

00:50:27.057 --> 00:50:28.390
He says, I know it sounds weird.

00:50:28.390 --> 00:50:31.395
He said, but for my sake,
he said, check it out.

00:50:31.395 --> 00:50:33.270
And that was in the
summer before my freshman

00:50:33.270 --> 00:50:33.936
year in college.

00:50:33.936 --> 00:50:36.660
Luckily, I found a meditation
instructor that year,

00:50:36.660 --> 00:50:39.330
my freshman year in college, and
I started because of my friend.

00:50:39.330 --> 00:50:42.250
And that's how I started,
and it went on from there.

00:50:42.250 --> 00:50:43.750
AUDIENCE: The
courses you mentioned

00:50:43.750 --> 00:50:45.320
are really for the [INAUDIBLE].

00:50:45.320 --> 00:50:46.870
What about for the civilians?

00:50:46.870 --> 00:50:48.500
Like, I'm really
interested in starting

00:50:48.500 --> 00:50:49.930
on the path of meditation.

00:50:49.930 --> 00:50:53.930
I agree that in the 15
minutes, I am more calmer.

00:50:53.930 --> 00:50:56.580
When I stepped into this
room, I was very anxious

00:50:56.580 --> 00:50:58.420
about a lot of things.

00:50:58.420 --> 00:51:00.576
I am way more calmer, and
I feel that, you know,

00:51:00.576 --> 00:51:03.660
I have certain solutions
to my issues now.

00:51:03.660 --> 00:51:06.410
So I'm really wondering, how
can I get introduced to it

00:51:06.410 --> 00:51:07.732
and kind of pursue it?

00:51:07.732 --> 00:51:09.690
JOHN OSBORNE: There's
many kinds of meditation.

00:51:09.690 --> 00:51:12.023
I understand you already have
meditation and mindfulness

00:51:12.023 --> 00:51:13.670
being taught here.

00:51:13.670 --> 00:51:16.830
This breathing meditation
is an especially powerful

00:51:16.830 --> 00:51:20.170
introductory version of
meditation or introduction

00:51:20.170 --> 00:51:21.530
to meditation.

00:51:21.530 --> 00:51:23.430
For people like
the vets, something

00:51:23.430 --> 00:51:26.116
as subtle as mindfulness
is beyond their grasp.

00:51:26.116 --> 00:51:27.740
But the breathing
meditation brings you

00:51:27.740 --> 00:51:30.065
to a very, very deep
place very quickly.

00:51:30.065 --> 00:51:32.440
And you're lucky that you have
some people in Google that

00:51:32.440 --> 00:51:34.070
actually teach that
form of meditation.

00:51:34.070 --> 00:51:36.240
One of them's right
over there, Mark Ball.

00:51:36.240 --> 00:51:40.871
He's one of my-- I respect
Mark's teaching more than many,

00:51:40.871 --> 00:51:42.120
many other people that I know.

00:51:42.120 --> 00:51:43.830
You're very lucky to
have him at Google.

00:51:43.830 --> 00:51:45.825
And I believe he offers courses
in this breathing meditation.

00:51:45.825 --> 00:51:46.530
Is that right?

00:51:46.530 --> 00:51:47.230
MARK BALL: Yes.

00:51:47.230 --> 00:51:47.870
JOHN OSBORNE: Periodically.

00:51:47.870 --> 00:51:49.360
So see Mark if
you're interested.

00:51:49.360 --> 00:51:51.590
We do teach civilians.

00:51:51.590 --> 00:51:54.225
I teach a program that
teaches in corporations.

00:51:54.225 --> 00:51:56.350
I've taught at Harvard
Business School and Wharton.

00:51:56.350 --> 00:51:58.170
And a lot of people
are understanding now

00:51:58.170 --> 00:52:03.820
that the greatest resource that
any company like Google has

00:52:03.820 --> 00:52:06.684
is the resource that's in here.

00:52:06.684 --> 00:52:08.850
And we don't always have
full access to that, right?

00:52:08.850 --> 00:52:10.360
You didn't have full
access to that resource

00:52:10.360 --> 00:52:12.280
when you walked in here today,
right, because of your anxiety

00:52:12.280 --> 00:52:13.080
and whatever.

00:52:13.080 --> 00:52:16.680
So whatever a company can do
to maximize people's access

00:52:16.680 --> 00:52:18.320
to that resource
is going to show up

00:52:18.320 --> 00:52:21.110
in many, many ways for the
benefit of the company.

00:52:21.110 --> 00:52:23.347
So when I'm not teaching
vets, sometimes I

00:52:23.347 --> 00:52:24.930
teach people in
corporate environments

00:52:24.930 --> 00:52:26.269
around the country.

00:52:26.269 --> 00:52:28.060
Once again, I'd like
to thank [? Ruchica ?]

00:52:28.060 --> 00:52:30.650
and her colleagues and everybody
at Google for having me

00:52:30.650 --> 00:52:31.180
here today.

00:52:31.180 --> 00:52:32.130
Thank you very much.

00:52:32.130 --> 00:52:35.180
[APPLAUSE]

